<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: IRVINE; MEETING TO DISCUSS CLEARED RIGHT-OF-WAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The last of the rusting tracks were removed from a 1.3-mile railroad 
right-of-way in 1984. And for most of the last decade, Northwood village 
residents and city officials have been debating what to do with the land. 
</P>
<P>
 Plans to transform the undeveloped land into a park will take a major step 
forward with a community meeting this morning to discuss how to design the 
area. 
</P>
<P>
 The meeting will take place at 9 a.m. at Sierra Vista Middle School. 
</P>
<P>
 It will be moderated by Lawrence Halprin, a noted San Francisco landscape 
architect who volunteered his time for the effort. 
</P>
<P>
 Residents who live along the narrow strip of land hope the meeting is the 
first step in developing a park complete with a trail for walking and perhaps 
bike riding. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm very excited that we are finally at this point," said resident Ann 
Cleland, who lives next to the Northwood Abandoned Railroad Right of Way, or 
NARROW. 
</P>
<P>
 The meeting will give residents a chance to discuss ideas for the park with 
Halprin, and take a tour of the land. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials aren't sure how much it will cost to develop the site, but the bill 
is expect to run more than $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
 What to do with the right-of-way has been the subject of much debate over the 
last few years. 
</P>
<P>
 Residents opposed one proposal to make it part of a regional bike trail. 
</P>
<P>
 The idea of having residents buy chunks of land next to their homes was also 
ruled out. 
</P>
<P>
 The city settled on a plan for a "linear park" with a path running through it. 
</P>
<P>
 The land is an average of 65 feet wide, so Cleland doubts a playground or 
exercise circuit would fit in it. The right-of-way runs from Culver Drive to 
Jeffrey Road and is lined by homes. 
</P>
<P>
 Cleland said some residents are concerned about protecting the safety of 
pedestrians who must cross major streets such as Yale Avenue when walking the 
path. 
</P>
<P>
 Another issue likely to be discussed at the meeting is security and privacy. 
</P>
<P>
 Most homes that back up against the right-of-way are separated by walls, but 
the interiors of some homes remain visible.SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
