<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUTHS AT BAPTIST CONVENTION PLEDGE CHASTITY TILL MARRIAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 More than a thousand teen-agers at a Baptist convention signed cards vowing to 
remain virgins until marriage, joining other youths nationwide who have taken 
similar pledges of celibacy. 
</P>
<P>
 "Virginity is the greatest gift you can give your future mate," Seth 
Rodriquez, 17, said last week to cheers from other teen-agers at the Southern 
Baptist State Youth Conference. 
</P>
<P>
 Rodriquez was one of about 1,200 convention-goers who signed "True Love Waits" 
cards, pledging themselves to God and promising to remain chaste. 
</P>
<P>
 Other churches and organizations have joined the program. By July the 
coalition hopes to gather 500,000 signed pledges for display in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
 Rick Prall, youth pastor at El Toro Baptist Church, said he sees the campaign 
as a way to get youths thinking about the sacredness of their sexuality. 
</P>
<P>
 "My goal is to get them to make sexual choices now instead of waiting until 
they're in the back seat of a car," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
