<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHATSWORTH DUO DENIED ELIGIBILITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE ELLING 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Three former Faith Baptist High baseball players seeking athletic eligibility 
at City Section schools met with different fates Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 The hardship petitions of Chad Evanson and Mike Jimenez were denied, while 
Clint Marcus was granted eligibility.All are seniors. 
</P>
<P>
 Marcus attends El Camino Real. Evanson and Jimenez are enrolled at Chatsworth. 
All three claimed financial hardship. 
</P>
<P>
 Wayne Evanson, Chad's father, said he was told by City Section Commissioner 
Barbara Fiege that his annual income is sufficient to pay the tuition at a 
private school. 
</P>
<P>
 Jimenez, who couldn't be reached for comment, received the same news. Fiege 
also could not be reached. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's really confusing and frustrating," Wayne Evanson said. 
</P>
<P>
 The elder Evanson criticized the City for a series of delays that three times 
resulted in failure to reach a final verdict on his son's eligibility. 
</P>
<P>
 A decision was first expected last fall, but was delayed because of a backlog 
of cases. 
</P>
<P>
 The Evansons said they have scheduled a Jan. 22 meeting to appeal the 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
 Jimenez was contending for a starting outfield position. Evanson, a 
right-hander, was expected to be the team's No. 3 pitcher. STEVE ELLING 
</P>
</TEXT>
